{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499774"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1541"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1541"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.3,0.19,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96952"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79567"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"402"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37661"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96952"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive shortness of breath on exertion and fatigue. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears mildly distressed. His pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a displaced apex beat, a third heart sound, and bilateral ankle edema. Chest auscultation reveals fine bibasal crackles. An echocardiogram shows a dilated left ventricle with an ejection fraction of 30%. An ECG is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most associated with dilated cardiomyopathy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right bundle branch block","Prolonged PR interval","Poor R-wave progression","Right axis deviation","Non-specific ST-T wave changes and Q wave changes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENo ECG findings are unique to dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM). Common findings include LBBB, LVH, and \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-specific ST-T wave changes and Q wave changes\u003C/strong\u003E, representing a strain pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight bundle branch block \u003C/strong\u003Emay be observed in DCM secondary to right ventricular enlargement, but typically in DCM, left-sided changes are seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged PR interval \u003C/strong\u003Eis not typically associated with dilated cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor R-wave progression \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common finding that is not largely specific to DCM and may be a sign of fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight axis deviation \u003C/strong\u003Emay represent right ventricular hypertrophy in DCM, but again typically in DCM, left-sided changes are seen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dilated cardiomyopathy will cause ECG abnormalities mainly non specific in nature and may manifest as Non-specific ST-T wave changes and Q wave changes"],"references":["Edhouse J, Thakur RK, Khalil JM. ABC of clinical electrocardiography. Conditions affecting the left side of the heart. BMJ. 2002 May 25;324(7348):1264-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79567"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1541"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79567"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T20:10:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T20:56:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1541"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96952"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships